{{head|fr|particle|head=[[est]]-[[ce]] [[que]]}}

# {{n-g|Used to introduce a yes-or-no question.}}
#: {{uxi|fr|'''Est-ce que''' tu veux une chambre ?| Do you want a bedroom?}}
#: {{uxi|fr|'''Est-ce qu’'''elle est arrivée ?|Has she arrived?}}
# {{n-g|Used after a preposed interrogative to introduce the remainder of the question.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Quand '''est-ce que''' les élèves retournent à l’école ?|When do the students return to school?}}
#: {{ux|fr|Combien de musées '''est-ce qu’'''il y a en France ?|How many museums are there in France?}}

====Usage notes====
* Before a vowel, {{m|fr||est-ce que}} becomes {{m|fr||est-ce qu’}}:
*: {{m|fr||est-ce qu’elle}}
*: {{m|fr||est-ce qu’il}}
* In older forms of French, and in more formal registers of present-day French, the role of {{m|fr||est-ce que}} is often fulfilled by subject-verb inversion:
*: {{uxi|fr|Quand viendrez-vous ?|When will you come?}}
: In fact, {{m|fr|est-ce que}} itself results from subject-verb inversion; it comes from {{m|fr||c’est que}} — ''however'', in modern French, {{m|fr|est-ce que}} is a set phrase that does not necessarily function as the inversion of {{m|fr||c’est que}} and the former can be used to introduce a question beginning with the latter:
:: {{ux|fr|'''Est-ce que c'est que''' les hommes sont partis ? |Have the men left?}}
* In colloquial French, yes-or-no questions are often indicated solely by punctuation (in writing) or intonation (in speech), with no special lexical or syntactic marker:
*: {{uxi|fr|T'es prête ?|You ready?}}
: Similarly, non–yes-or-no questions often use the same structure as statements, with question words not being preposed:
:: {{uxi|fr|Il a dit quoi ?|He said what?}}
* In informal or colloquial French, question syntax is often used instead of subject-verb inversion in indirect questions:
*: {{ux|fr|Il veut savoir où '''est-ce qu’'''ils habitent.|He wants to know where ('''it is that''') they live.}}

